/* CCSP :: content/quiz2.js — CCSP Domain 2 question bank (100 items). */
window.CCSP = window.CCSP || {}; CCSP.questions = CCSP.questions || [];
CCSP.questions.push.apply(CCSP.questions, [{"id":"D2-001","domain":2,"obj":"2.1","diff":"easy","q":"A cloud architect is documenting the cloud secure data lifecycle for a new SaaS onboarding. In which phase is data first generated or modified and therefore where classification labels should first be applied?","options":["Create","Store","Use","Archive"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Create</strong> — the Create phase is where data is generated, imported, or modified, making it the earliest and cheapest point to classify and label data so downstream controls follow it.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Store</b>: storage happens after creation; committing to storage without a label already applied means controls may be misapplied.</span><span class='qd'><b>Use</b>: Use is when data is processed or viewed, well after it exists and should already be classified.</span><span class='qd'><b>Archive</b>: archiving is near the end of the lifecycle for long-term retention, far too late to be the first classification point.</span>"},{"id":"D2-002","domain":2,"obj":"2.1","diff":"easy","q":"During which cloud data lifecycle phase is data most commonly transmitted between applications, users, or external parties, making transport-layer protection the primary concern?","options":["Destroy","Share","Create","Store"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Share</strong> — the Share phase covers data made accessible to others inside or outside the organization, so TLS, IRM, and DLP egress controls are the dominant protections.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Destroy</b>: Destroy focuses on secure disposal such as crypto-shredding, not on transmission.</span><span class='qd'><b>Create</b>: Create is generation of data, where classification not transport is the concern.</span><span class='qd'><b>Store</b>: Store concerns data at rest, where encryption of the repository is the primary control.</span>"},{"id":"D2-003","domain":2,"obj":"2.1","diff":"medium","q":"A provider distributes fragments of each stored object across multiple physical nodes and zones so no single node holds a complete copy. This technique primarily supports which cloud data concept?","options":["Data flow mapping","Tokenization","Data dispersion","Legal hold"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Data dispersion</strong> — data dispersion (a cloud analog of RAID/erasure coding) fragments and spreads data across nodes and locations for resiliency and to reduce the value of any single compromised node.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Data flow mapping</b>: data flow mapping documents how data moves between systems, not how it is fragmented at rest.</span><span class='qd'><b>Tokenization</b>: tokenization substitutes a surrogate value for a sensitive field, not fragmentation across nodes.</span><span class='qd'><b>Legal hold</b>: legal hold preserves data for litigation and is unrelated to physical fragmentation.</span>"},{"id":"D2-004","domain":2,"obj":"2.1","diff":"medium","q":"A security advisor wants to identify every place regulated PII enters, transits, and leaves a hybrid environment before designing controls. Which activity most directly produces that understanding?","options":["Building a DLP policy","Selecting a KMS","Writing a retention schedule","Creating data flow diagrams"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Creating data flow diagrams</strong> — data flow mapping traces where data originates, where it moves, where it rests, and where it exits, which is the prerequisite for placing the right controls at the right points.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Building a DLP policy</b>: DLP is a control you apply after you understand the flows; it does not by itself reveal them.</span><span class='qd'><b>Selecting a KMS</b>: key management supports encryption but does not map how data moves.</span><span class='qd'><b>Writing a retention schedule</b>: retention governs how long data is kept, not where it flows.</span>"},{"id":"D2-005","domain":2,"obj":"2.1","diff":"hard","q":"An organization argues that because data is encrypted at rest it need not classify data during the Create phase. What is the most defensible CCSP critique of this position?","options":["Classification drives which controls apply, so encryption alone cannot substitute for it","Encryption at rest already satisfies classification requirements","Classification is only required during the Archive phase","Encryption should be applied only during the Share phase"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Classification drives which controls apply, so encryption alone cannot substitute for it</strong> — classification determines handling, access, retention, and legal obligations; encryption is one possible control, not a replacement for knowing the data's sensitivity.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Encryption at rest already satisfies classification requirements</b>: encryption protects confidentiality but tells you nothing about handling, retention, or regulatory scope.</span><span class='qd'><b>Classification is only required during the Archive phase</b>: classification is cheapest and most effective at Create, and is needed throughout the lifecycle.</span><span class='qd'><b>Encryption should be applied only during the Share phase</b>: at-rest data in Store also needs protection; limiting encryption to Share leaves stored data exposed.</span>"},{"id":"D2-006","domain":2,"obj":"2.1","diff":"easy","q":"Which cloud data lifecycle phase is specifically concerned with permanently removing data such that it can no longer be recovered?","options":["Archive","Destroy","Store","Use"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Destroy</strong> — the Destroy phase covers permanent, irreversible removal of data, typically via crypto-shredding or secure overwriting in the cloud.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Archive</b>: Archive retains data for long-term storage, the opposite of destruction.</span><span class='qd'><b>Store</b>: Store commits active data to a repository; it does not remove it.</span><span class='qd'><b>Use</b>: Use is processing or viewing of data, not disposal.</span>"},{"id":"D2-007","domain":2,"obj":"2.1","diff":"medium","q":"A team notes that data in the Use phase is often decrypted in memory for processing. Which emerging technology most directly reduces exposure of data while it is in use?","options":["Object versioning","DNSSEC","Confidential computing","Erasure coding"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Confidential computing</strong> — confidential computing uses hardware-based trusted execution environments to keep data encrypted even while being processed, protecting data-in-use during the Use phase.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Object versioning</b>: versioning retains prior copies of stored objects; it does nothing for in-memory data.</span><span class='qd'><b>DNSSEC</b>: DNSSEC authenticates DNS responses and is unrelated to protecting data in memory.</span><span class='qd'><b>Erasure coding</b>: erasure coding provides storage resiliency, not runtime memory protection.</span>"},{"id":"D2-008","domain":2,"obj":"2.1","diff":"hard","q":"A cloud customer must ensure that when data transitions from Share back to Store, controls applied during sharing are not silently lost. What lifecycle principle best guides this?","options":["Controls should be reset at each phase boundary","Only the Store phase requires encryption","Sharing controls automatically carry to storage without design","Data-centric security should persist protection with the data across phases"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Data-centric security should persist protection with the data across phases</strong> — the secure data lifecycle is data-centric, meaning protections like encryption, labeling, and rights should travel with the data so transitions do not drop controls.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Controls should be reset at each phase boundary</b>: resetting controls creates gaps; protection should be continuous, not rebuilt each phase.</span><span class='qd'><b>Only the Store phase requires encryption</b>: multiple phases require protection; singling out Store leaves other phases exposed.</span><span class='qd'><b>Sharing controls automatically carry to storage without design</b>: nothing carries automatically; persistence must be deliberately designed, e.g. via IRM.</span>"},{"id":"D2-009","domain":2,"obj":"2.1","diff":"medium","q":"Regulators ask an organization to demonstrate the order of the cloud secure data lifecycle. Which sequence is correct?","options":["Create, Store, Use, Share, Archive, Destroy","Create, Use, Store, Archive, Share, Destroy","Store, Create, Share, Use, Destroy, Archive","Create, Share, Store, Use, Destroy, Archive"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Create, Store, Use, Share, Archive, Destroy</strong> — this is the canonical CCSP secure data lifecycle order, though data may loop among phases.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Create, Use, Store, Archive, Share, Destroy</b>: it places Use before Store and Archive before Share, which is out of the canonical order.</span><span class='qd'><b>Store, Create, Share, Use, Destroy, Archive</b>: data cannot be stored before it is created, and Destroy is the final phase, not Archive.</span><span class='qd'><b>Create, Share, Store, Use, Destroy, Archive</b>: Share appears before Store and Use, and Archive follows Destroy, both incorrect.</span>"},{"id":"D2-010","domain":2,"obj":"2.1","diff":"easy","q":"An auditor asks which lifecycle phase moves data from active production repositories into long-term, lower-cost retention while keeping it recoverable. Which phase is this?","options":["Destroy","Archive","Create","Use"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Archive</strong> — the Archive phase moves data into long-term retention that is still recoverable, distinct from permanent destruction.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Destroy</b>: Destroy permanently and irreversibly removes data, not retains it.</span><span class='qd'><b>Create</b>: Create is initial generation of data, not long-term retention.</span><span class='qd'><b>Use</b>: Use is active processing, not movement to cold retention.</span>"},{"id":"D2-011","domain":2,"obj":"2.2","diff":"easy","q":"A developer needs a cloud storage type that stores unstructured data as objects with rich metadata, accessed over HTTP APIs rather than as mounted volumes. Which storage type fits?","options":["Block/volume storage","Ephemeral storage","Object storage","Database storage"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Object storage</strong> — object storage holds unstructured data as objects with metadata and unique identifiers, accessed via REST APIs, ideal for large unstructured datasets.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Block/volume storage</b>: volume storage presents raw block devices mounted to instances, not API-accessed objects.</span><span class='qd'><b>Ephemeral storage</b>: ephemeral storage is temporary instance-local storage lost on termination, not durable object storage.</span><span class='qd'><b>Database storage</b>: database storage manages structured records via a DBMS, not arbitrary objects with metadata.</span>"},{"id":"D2-012","domain":2,"obj":"2.2","diff":"easy","q":"Which storage type is attached to a compute instance, persists only for the life of that instance, and is lost when the instance is terminated?","options":["Object storage","Long-term storage","Archive storage","Ephemeral storage"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Ephemeral storage</strong> — ephemeral storage is temporary, instance-attached storage whose contents are lost when the instance stops or terminates.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Object storage</b>: object storage is durable and independent of any instance lifecycle.</span><span class='qd'><b>Long-term storage</b>: long-term storage persists for extended retention, the opposite of ephemeral.</span><span class='qd'><b>Archive storage</b>: archive storage is durable cold storage for retention, not tied to instance life.</span>"},{"id":"D2-013","domain":2,"obj":"2.2","diff":"medium","q":"A database team wants block-level storage that can be attached to a single instance and formatted with a file system for a transactional workload. Which storage type is the best match?","options":["Volume storage","Object storage","Content delivery cache","Raw archival storage"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Volume storage</strong> — volume (block) storage presents raw block devices that can be attached to an instance and formatted with a file system, suiting transactional databases needing low-latency block I/O.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Object storage</b>: object storage is not block-addressable and is unsuitable for a formatted transactional file system.</span><span class='qd'><b>Content delivery cache</b>: a CDN cache serves distributed read content, not a mounted transactional volume.</span><span class='qd'><b>Raw archival storage</b>: archival storage is cold retention with high retrieval latency, wrong for active transactions.</span>"},{"id":"D2-014","domain":2,"obj":"2.2","diff":"medium","q":"A security review flags that an object storage bucket was made publicly readable, exposing customer files. Which storage threat category does this misconfiguration best represent?","options":["Media degradation","Improper access controls / exposure","Data remanence on decommissioned drives","Vendor lock-in"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Improper access controls / exposure</strong> — a public bucket is an access-control failure that exposes stored objects, one of the most common cloud object-storage threats.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Media degradation</b>: media degradation concerns physical decay of storage media, not permissions.</span><span class='qd'><b>Data remanence on decommissioned drives</b>: remanence is leftover data on retired media, not an active public bucket.</span><span class='qd'><b>Vendor lock-in</b>: lock-in is a portability concern, unrelated to this exposure.</span>"},{"id":"D2-015","domain":2,"obj":"2.2","diff":"medium","q":"An architect is concerned that in a multi-tenant object store, a flaw could let one tenant read another tenant's data. Which threat to storage is this?","options":["Data dispersion","Ephemeral data loss","Cross-tenant isolation failure","Legal hold conflict"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Cross-tenant isolation failure</strong> — multi-tenancy introduces the threat that weak logical isolation lets one tenant access another's data, a core cloud storage risk.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Data dispersion</b>: dispersion is a resiliency technique, not a threat.</span><span class='qd'><b>Ephemeral data loss</b>: that concerns temporary storage disappearing, not tenant boundary breaches.</span><span class='qd'><b>Legal hold conflict</b>: legal hold relates to preservation obligations, not tenant isolation.</span>"},{"id":"D2-016","domain":2,"obj":"2.2","diff":"hard","q":"A team must choose storage for streaming intermediate results that are recomputed if lost and must never persist after the job ends for compliance reasons. Which storage type best satisfies both goals?","options":["Durable object storage with versioning","Long-term archival storage","Replicated database storage","Ephemeral storage"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Ephemeral storage</strong> — ephemeral storage is instance-local and automatically discarded when the job ends, satisfying the no-persistence requirement, and the recomputable data tolerates its volatility.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Durable object storage with versioning</b>: versioning deliberately retains prior copies, violating the no-persistence requirement.</span><span class='qd'><b>Long-term archival storage</b>: archival retains data for years, the opposite of what is required.</span><span class='qd'><b>Replicated database storage</b>: replication persists and copies data, again contradicting the requirement that nothing remain.</span>"},{"id":"D2-017","domain":2,"obj":"2.2","diff":"hard","q":"A CCSP advisor evaluates a threat where an attacker who gains storage-account credentials could enumerate and exfiltrate every object. Beyond access control, which storage-layer control most limits the damage if credentials are stolen?","options":["Encrypting objects with customer-managed keys held separately","Enabling object versioning","Increasing storage redundancy","Compressing objects at rest"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Encrypting objects with customer-managed keys held separately</strong> — if the ciphertext is protected by keys the attacker cannot reach, stolen storage credentials yield only unreadable data, limiting exfiltration damage.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Enabling object versioning</b>: versioning protects against overwrite/deletion but does nothing to stop an attacker reading current data.</span><span class='qd'><b>Increasing storage redundancy</b>: redundancy improves availability, not confidentiality against a credentialed attacker.</span><span class='qd'><b>Compressing objects at rest</b>: compression saves space and is not a confidentiality control.</span>"},{"id":"D2-018","domain":2,"obj":"2.2","diff":"medium","q":"Which threat is most specific to long-term archival cloud storage as opposed to hot object storage?","options":["A publicly exposed bucket","Data becoming unreadable due to obsolete formats or lost keys over time","API rate limiting","TLS downgrade during upload"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Data becoming unreadable due to obsolete formats or lost keys over time</strong> — long retention introduces the risk that formats, applications, or encryption keys become unavailable, rendering archived data unrecoverable.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A publicly exposed bucket</b>: exposure is a general access-control threat, not specific to archival retention.</span><span class='qd'><b>API rate limiting</b>: rate limiting is an availability/operational concern, not an archival-specific threat.</span><span class='qd'><b>TLS downgrade during upload</b>: that is a transport threat during data-in-transit, unrelated to long-term archival readability.</span>"},{"id":"D2-019","domain":2,"obj":"2.2","diff":"easy","q":"Which cloud storage type is most appropriate for a shared network file system that multiple instances mount simultaneously with POSIX semantics?","options":["Object storage","Block storage","File storage","Ephemeral storage"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>File storage</strong> — file storage provides a shared, hierarchical file system with POSIX semantics that multiple instances can mount concurrently.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Object storage</b>: object storage is accessed via API and lacks POSIX file-system semantics for concurrent mounts.</span><span class='qd'><b>Block storage</b>: block volumes typically attach to a single instance and lack a shared file namespace.</span><span class='qd'><b>Ephemeral storage</b>: ephemeral storage is local and volatile, not a shared network file system.</span>"},{"id":"D2-020","domain":2,"obj":"2.3","diff":"easy","q":"An organization wants to render production PII unusable in a lower test environment while preserving realistic format for developers. Which technique is most appropriate?","options":["Full-disk encryption","Digital signing","Compression","Data masking"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Data masking</strong> — masking replaces sensitive values with realistic but fictitious data so non-production environments retain usable format without exposing real PII.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Full-disk encryption</b>: encryption protects data at rest but developers with access would still see decrypted real PII.</span><span class='qd'><b>Digital signing</b>: signing provides integrity/authenticity, not confidentiality of the values.</span><span class='qd'><b>Compression</b>: compression reduces size and does not obscure sensitive content.</span>"},{"id":"D2-021","domain":2,"obj":"2.3","diff":"medium","q":"A payment application must remove card numbers from its databases while still allowing a reversible lookup through a secure vault for settlement. Which technique fits best?","options":["Tokenization","Static data masking","One-way hashing","Anonymization"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Tokenization</strong> — tokenization replaces the card number with a surrogate token while the real value is retained in a secure vault, allowing authorized reversible lookup and removing PANs from the app database.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Static data masking</b>: masking is typically irreversible and used for non-production data, not settlement lookups.</span><span class='qd'><b>One-way hashing</b>: hashing is irreversible, so the original card number could not be recovered for settlement.</span><span class='qd'><b>Anonymization</b>: anonymization intentionally severs the link to the original, preventing the reversible lookup required.</span>"},{"id":"D2-022","domain":2,"obj":"2.3","diff":"medium","q":"A cloud customer wants to ensure the provider's administrators cannot read its encrypted data even though the data resides in the provider's storage. Which key-management approach best achieves this?","options":["Provider-managed keys with default encryption","Customer-managed keys where the customer controls the KMS/HSM","Server-side encryption with provider-held keys only","Disabling encryption and relying on network isolation"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Customer-managed keys where the customer controls the KMS/HSM</strong> — when the customer holds and controls the keys (ideally in its own or a dedicated HSM), the provider cannot decrypt the data, enforcing separation of duties.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Provider-managed keys with default encryption</b>: if the provider holds the keys it can technically decrypt the data, defeating the goal.</span><span class='qd'><b>Server-side encryption with provider-held keys only</b>: provider-held keys again leave decryption capability with the provider.</span><span class='qd'><b>Disabling encryption and relying on network isolation</b>: no encryption means the data is plainly readable to anyone with storage access.</span>"},{"id":"D2-023","domain":2,"obj":"2.3","diff":"easy","q":"Which technique produces a fixed-length, one-way value used to verify that a file has not been altered?","options":["Tokenization","Masking","Hashing","Anonymization"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Hashing</strong> — a cryptographic hash produces a fixed-length, one-way digest used to verify integrity, since any change to the input changes the output.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Tokenization</b>: tokenization substitutes a reversible surrogate value, not a one-way integrity digest.</span><span class='qd'><b>Masking</b>: masking obscures values for confidentiality in non-production data, not integrity verification.</span><span class='qd'><b>Anonymization</b>: anonymization removes identifiability; it is not an integrity check.</span>"},{"id":"D2-024","domain":2,"obj":"2.3","diff":"medium","q":"A DLP program must stop confidential design documents from being uploaded to unsanctioned external services. Which DLP deployment point is most relevant to this egress use case?","options":["Data-at-rest DLP scanning storage","Data-in-use DLP on endpoints only","Backup integrity checking","Data-in-motion DLP at the network egress"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Data-in-motion DLP at the network egress</strong> — inspecting traffic leaving the environment lets DLP detect and block confidential documents being uploaded to unsanctioned destinations.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Data-at-rest DLP scanning storage</b>: at-rest scanning finds where sensitive data is stored but does not block an outbound upload in progress.</span><span class='qd'><b>Data-in-use DLP on endpoints only</b>: endpoint-only coverage misses uploads from other systems and does not address network egress broadly.</span><span class='qd'><b>Backup integrity checking</b>: backup integrity is unrelated to preventing external uploads.</span>"},{"id":"D2-025","domain":2,"obj":"2.3","diff":"hard","q":"An analyst says a dataset is 'anonymized' because names were removed, yet birthdate, ZIP, and gender remain. What is the strongest CCSP objection?","options":["Quasi-identifiers can enable re-identification, so this is at best pseudonymization","Removing names always achieves anonymization","Tokenization was required instead","Hashing the names would have anonymized the set"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Quasi-identifiers can enable re-identification, so this is at best pseudonymization</strong> — combinations of quasi-identifiers like birthdate, ZIP, and gender can re-identify individuals, so removing direct identifiers alone does not achieve true anonymization.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Removing names always achieves anonymization</b>: this is precisely the flawed assumption; quasi-identifiers defeat it.</span><span class='qd'><b>Tokenization was required instead</b>: tokenization is reversible and used for operational protection, not a substitute for proper anonymization here.</span><span class='qd'><b>Hashing the names would have anonymized the set</b>: hashing names still leaves re-identifying quasi-identifiers untouched.</span>"},{"id":"D2-026","domain":2,"obj":"2.3","diff":"medium","q":"An organization needs a tamper-resistant, certified hardware boundary to generate and store the root keys protecting all cloud-encrypted data. Which component should it use?","options":["A software password vault","A hardware security module (HSM)","A CDN edge node","A container registry"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>A hardware security module (HSM)</strong> — an HSM is a hardened, often FIPS 140-validated device that generates and protects cryptographic keys within a tamper-resistant boundary, ideal for root/master keys.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A software password vault</b>: a software vault lacks the certified tamper-resistant hardware boundary required for high-assurance root keys.</span><span class='qd'><b>A CDN edge node</b>: a CDN caches content and has no role in protecting master keys.</span><span class='qd'><b>A container registry</b>: a registry stores images, unrelated to key generation and protection.</span>"},{"id":"D2-027","domain":2,"obj":"2.3","diff":"hard","q":"A CCSP is asked why key rotation alone does not protect data if the same key-encryption key wraps every data key and is stored beside the ciphertext. What principle is most violated?","options":["Least privilege","Defense in depth against DDoS","Separation of keys from the data they protect","Data minimization"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Separation of keys from the data they protect</strong> — storing the wrapping key alongside the ciphertext means anyone who reaches the data also reaches the key, so rotation cannot compensate for the lack of key/data separation.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Least privilege</b>: least privilege concerns access rights, not the physical/logical co-location of keys and ciphertext.</span><span class='qd'><b>Defense in depth against DDoS</b>: DDoS is an availability threat, irrelevant to key confidentiality here.</span><span class='qd'><b>Data minimization</b>: minimization limits collected data, not how keys are stored relative to data.</span>"},{"id":"D2-028","domain":2,"obj":"2.3","diff":"easy","q":"Which term describes the practice of centrally storing and controlling access to API keys, database passwords, and certificates used by cloud workloads?","options":["Data dispersion","Federation","Object versioning","Secrets management"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Secrets management</strong> — secrets management centrally issues, stores, rotates, and controls access to credentials, keys, and certificates for workloads.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Data dispersion</b>: dispersion spreads data fragments for resiliency, not credential control.</span><span class='qd'><b>Federation</b>: federation links identity across domains, not the storage of workload secrets.</span><span class='qd'><b>Object versioning</b>: versioning retains prior object copies, unrelated to secrets.</span>"},{"id":"D2-029","domain":2,"obj":"2.3","diff":"medium","q":"A team must choose between encryption and tokenization for protecting PANs so that downstream analytics never touch real card numbers but format is preserved for joins. Which best fits and why?","options":["Tokenization, because format-preserving tokens keep referential integrity without exposing PANs","Encryption, because ciphertext preserves referential format","Hashing, because it is reversible for analytics","Masking, because it supports secure joins across systems"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Tokenization, because format-preserving tokens keep referential integrity without exposing PANs</strong> — format-preserving tokens can substitute PANs consistently, preserving the ability to join records while keeping real card numbers out of analytics.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Encryption, because ciphertext preserves referential format</b>: standard ciphertext usually changes length/format and is not designed for consistent join keys.</span><span class='qd'><b>Hashing, because it is reversible for analytics</b>: hashing is not reversible, contradicting the stated reasoning.</span><span class='qd'><b>Masking, because it supports secure joins across systems</b>: masking is typically inconsistent and for non-production use, not reliable cross-system joins.</span>"},{"id":"D2-030","domain":2,"obj":"2.3","diff":"hard","q":"An advisor recommends 'bring your own key' (BYOK) but a stakeholder wants stronger control where the provider never has the key material even transiently. Which model best meets that stricter requirement?","options":["Provider-managed keys","Hold your own key (HYOK) with external key store","BYOK with provider-imported keys","Server-side default encryption"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Hold your own key (HYOK) with external key store</strong> — HYOK keeps key material in a customer-controlled external key store so the provider must call out for cryptographic operations and never holds the key, exceeding BYOK's guarantees.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Provider-managed keys</b>: the provider holds and controls the keys, the weakest control for this requirement.</span><span class='qd'><b>BYOK with provider-imported keys</b>: with BYOK the customer supplies the key but the provider imports and can use it internally, so it may hold material transiently.</span><span class='qd'><b>Server-side default encryption</b>: default encryption uses provider keys, giving the customer no exclusive control.</span>"},{"id":"D2-031","domain":2,"obj":"2.4","diff":"easy","q":"A discovery tool is pointed at relational databases where data resides in defined tables, rows, and columns. This data is best described as which type?","options":["Unstructured","Semi-structured","Structured","Ephemeral"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Structured</strong> — data organized into predefined tables, rows, and columns with a fixed schema is structured data, typically found in relational databases.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Unstructured</b>: unstructured data lacks a predefined model, such as free-text documents or images.</span><span class='qd'><b>Semi-structured</b>: semi-structured data uses tags or markers (JSON, XML) but not a rigid relational schema.</span><span class='qd'><b>Ephemeral</b>: ephemeral describes storage volatility, not a data structure category.</span>"},{"id":"D2-032","domain":2,"obj":"2.4","diff":"easy","q":"Emails, PDFs, images, and free-text notes stored in an object store are examples of which data category for discovery purposes?","options":["Structured","Semi-structured","Tokenized","Unstructured"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Unstructured</strong> — content without a predefined data model, such as documents, images, and free text, is unstructured data and is the hardest to discover and classify.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Structured</b>: structured data has a fixed schema of rows and columns, unlike free-form files.</span><span class='qd'><b>Semi-structured</b>: semi-structured data carries self-describing tags like XML/JSON, which these examples generally lack.</span><span class='qd'><b>Tokenized</b>: tokenized is a protection state, not a discovery data category.</span>"},{"id":"D2-033","domain":2,"obj":"2.4","diff":"medium","q":"A discovery initiative must handle JSON and XML documents that carry embedded tags describing their fields but no rigid table schema. Which data type and discovery approach applies?","options":["Semi-structured data, discovered via parsing tags and elements","Structured data, best discovered via schema crawling of tables","Unstructured data, discovered only via manual review","Ephemeral data, discovered via memory dumps"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Semi-structured data, discovered via parsing tags and elements</strong> — JSON/XML is semi-structured because self-describing tags define fields without a fixed relational schema, so parsers that read those tags are the right discovery approach.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Structured data, best discovered via schema crawling of tables</b>: JSON/XML lacks a fixed relational table schema, so table crawling misses the tag-based structure.</span><span class='qd'><b>Unstructured data, discovered only via manual review</b>: these documents are self-describing via tags, so they are not unstructured and can be parsed automatically.</span><span class='qd'><b>Ephemeral data, discovered via memory dumps</b>: ephemeral refers to storage volatility, not to tagged document formats.</span>"},{"id":"D2-034","domain":2,"obj":"2.4","diff":"medium","q":"A CCSP notes that in the cloud, data discovery must first answer 'where does our data physically and jurisdictionally reside?' Why is data location a foundational discovery concern?","options":["Because location changes the file format","Because location determines applicable laws, regulations, and control obligations","Because location has no effect on compliance","Because location only matters for backups"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Because location determines applicable laws, regulations, and control obligations</strong> — data residency drives which legal and regulatory regimes apply, so knowing where data lives is foundational to discovery and compliance.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Because location changes the file format</b>: physical location has no bearing on file format.</span><span class='qd'><b>Because location has no effect on compliance</b>: this is the opposite of reality; residency is central to compliance.</span><span class='qd'><b>Because location only matters for backups</b>: location matters for all data, not just backups.</span>"},{"id":"D2-035","domain":2,"obj":"2.4","diff":"hard","q":"A team's discovery tool catalogs structured databases well but repeatedly misses sensitive data pasted into wiki pages and chat exports. What is the most likely root cause and remedy?","options":["The databases are misclassified; reclassify them","The tool needs faster storage; upgrade disks","The tool lacks content-inspection for unstructured sources; add pattern/ML-based scanning of those repositories","Encryption is blocking discovery; disable it"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>The tool lacks content-inspection for unstructured sources; add pattern/ML-based scanning of those repositories</strong> — wikis and chat exports are unstructured, requiring content inspection (regex, dictionaries, ML) rather than schema crawling to surface hidden sensitive data.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The databases are misclassified; reclassify them</b>: the gap is in unstructured sources, not the already-cataloged databases.</span><span class='qd'><b>The tool needs faster storage; upgrade disks</b>: performance is unrelated to failing to inspect unstructured content.</span><span class='qd'><b>Encryption is blocking discovery; disable it</b>: disabling encryption weakens security and does not address the unstructured-content gap.</span>"},{"id":"D2-036","domain":2,"obj":"2.4","diff":"medium","q":"Which challenge makes data discovery uniquely difficult in cloud environments compared to a single on-premises data center?","options":["Cloud data never moves once stored","Cloud eliminates the need to discover data","Discovery is only required for structured data","Data may be dispersed across regions, services, and providers with limited visibility"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Data may be dispersed across regions, services, and providers with limited visibility</strong> — cloud dispersion, multi-service sprawl, and provider abstraction reduce visibility, complicating discovery relative to a contained on-premises environment.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Cloud data never moves once stored</b>: cloud data frequently replicates and migrates across regions and services.</span><span class='qd'><b>Cloud eliminates the need to discover data</b>: the cloud increases, not removes, the need for discovery.</span><span class='qd'><b>Discovery is only required for structured data</b>: unstructured and semi-structured data also require discovery, often more urgently.</span>"},{"id":"D2-037","domain":2,"obj":"2.4","diff":"hard","q":"An organization wants data discovery to feed classification automatically at scale across petabytes of mixed content. Which capability is most essential to make this practical?","options":["Automated content inspection with pattern matching and machine learning","Manual reviewer sign-off on every file","Disabling metadata to speed scans","Storing all data in one bucket"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Automated content inspection with pattern matching and machine learning</strong> — at petabyte scale, automated inspection using patterns and ML is essential to identify and classify sensitive content without human review of every item.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Manual reviewer sign-off on every file</b>: manual review cannot scale to petabytes and defeats automation.</span><span class='qd'><b>Disabling metadata to speed scans</b>: metadata aids discovery and classification; disabling it hurts accuracy.</span><span class='qd'><b>Storing all data in one bucket</b>: consolidating storage does not solve the need to inspect and classify content.</span>"},{"id":"D2-038","domain":2,"obj":"2.4","diff":"easy","q":"For discovery purposes, which statement best distinguishes structured from unstructured data?","options":["Unstructured data is always encrypted; structured data is not","Structured data follows a predefined schema; unstructured data does not","Structured data is always in the cloud; unstructured data is on-premises","There is no meaningful difference for discovery"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Structured data follows a predefined schema; unstructured data does not</strong> — the defining distinction is the presence of a predefined data model, which shapes how each type is discovered.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Unstructured data is always encrypted; structured data is not</b>: encryption state is independent of structure.</span><span class='qd'><b>Structured data is always in the cloud; unstructured data is on-premises</b>: location does not determine structure.</span><span class='qd'><b>There is no meaningful difference for discovery</b>: the difference is central, as each needs different discovery methods.</span>"},{"id":"D2-039","domain":2,"obj":"2.1","diff":"medium","q":"A compliance officer wants controls tied to how sensitive data actually moves between a SaaS front end, a PaaS API tier, and an IaaS database. Which artifact should be produced first?","options":["A key rotation schedule","A DLP incident report","A documented data flow across the three tiers","A backup retention policy"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>A documented data flow across the three tiers</strong> — mapping the data flow between SaaS, PaaS, and IaaS tiers reveals where sensitive data crosses trust boundaries so controls can be placed accurately.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A key rotation schedule</b>: rotation is an operational control applied after flows are understood.</span><span class='qd'><b>A DLP incident report</b>: an incident report is reactive and does not proactively map how data moves.</span><span class='qd'><b>A backup retention policy</b>: retention governs how long copies are kept, not how data flows between tiers.</span>"},{"id":"D2-040","domain":2,"obj":"2.2","diff":"medium","q":"A workload uses raw storage exposed directly to an instance with no file system, later formatted by the guest OS. Which storage description matches 'raw' storage here?","options":["Object storage accessed by API","A managed relational database","A CDN cache tier","Unformatted block device presented to the instance"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Unformatted block device presented to the instance</strong> — raw storage is an unformatted block device given to the instance, which the guest OS then formats with a file system as needed.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Object storage accessed by API</b>: object storage is API-addressed, not a raw block device.</span><span class='qd'><b>A managed relational database</b>: a managed database abstracts storage entirely, the opposite of raw block access.</span><span class='qd'><b>A CDN cache tier</b>: a CDN caches content for delivery and is not raw block storage.</span>"},{"id":"D2-041","domain":2,"obj":"2.3","diff":"medium","q":"An organization must ensure that even if a database backup is stolen, individual sensitive fields remain protected without breaking application queries on non-sensitive columns. Which approach is most surgical?","options":["Field-level (column) encryption of sensitive attributes","Whole-instance disk encryption only","Network segmentation only","Disabling backups entirely"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Field-level (column) encryption of sensitive attributes</strong> — encrypting only sensitive columns keeps those fields protected in a stolen backup while leaving other columns queryable, a surgical, data-centric control.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Whole-instance disk encryption only</b>: disk encryption protects at rest on the live system but decrypted data or exported backups may still expose fields, and it is not field-selective.</span><span class='qd'><b>Network segmentation only</b>: segmentation limits access paths but does nothing to protect the fields inside a stolen backup.</span><span class='qd'><b>Disabling backups entirely</b>: removing backups harms availability and recoverability and is not a protection strategy.</span>"},{"id":"D2-042","domain":2,"obj":"2.3","diff":"hard","q":"A CCSP must advise on protecting data-in-use for a multi-tenant analytics service handling regulated data. Which combination best addresses confidentiality during processing?","options":["TLS in transit plus at-rest encryption only","Confidential computing enclaves plus strict tenant isolation","Object versioning plus longer retention","DNSSEC plus WAF rules"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Confidential computing enclaves plus strict tenant isolation</strong> — enclaves keep data encrypted during processing while strong tenant isolation prevents cross-tenant leakage, directly addressing data-in-use confidentiality.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>TLS in transit plus at-rest encryption only</b>: these protect data in transit and at rest but leave data decrypted in memory during processing.</span><span class='qd'><b>Object versioning plus longer retention</b>: these address recoverability and retention, not in-use confidentiality.</span><span class='qd'><b>DNSSEC plus WAF rules</b>: these protect name resolution and web requests, not data being processed in memory.</span>"},{"id":"D2-043","domain":2,"obj":"2.1","diff":"hard","q":"A provider replicates customer data to a second geographic region for durability. From a lifecycle and governance view, what must the customer verify before accepting this default?","options":["That replication improves upload speed","That replication disables encryption","That the replica region's jurisdiction and residency requirements are acceptable","That the replica is unclassified by default"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>That the replica region's jurisdiction and residency requirements are acceptable</strong> — cross-region replication can move data into a different legal jurisdiction, so the customer must confirm residency and regulatory acceptability before accepting it.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>That replication improves upload speed</b>: durability replication is not primarily about upload speed and misses the governance concern.</span><span class='qd'><b>That replication disables encryption</b>: replication does not inherently disable encryption; this is not the governance issue.</span><span class='qd'><b>That the replica is unclassified by default</b>: replicas should inherit classification, not lose it; treating them as unclassified is a control failure.</span>"},{"id":"D2-044","domain":2,"obj":"2.2","diff":"medium","q":"Which threat is most directly associated with ephemeral storage specifically?","options":["A publicly writable object bucket","Certificate expiration in a secrets vault","Cross-region residency violations","Sensitive data unexpectedly persisting or being lost when the instance is recycled"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Sensitive data unexpectedly persisting or being lost when the instance is recycled</strong> — ephemeral storage's volatility creates twin threats: needed data lost on termination, and sensitive remnants left on shared underlying media when instances are recycled.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A publicly writable object bucket</b>: that is an object-storage access-control threat, not ephemeral-specific.</span><span class='qd'><b>Certificate expiration in a secrets vault</b>: that is a secrets-management issue, unrelated to ephemeral volatility.</span><span class='qd'><b>Cross-region residency violations</b>: residency is a governance concern across storage types, not specific to ephemeral storage.</span>"},{"id":"D2-045","domain":2,"obj":"2.3","diff":"easy","q":"Which obfuscation technique is designed to be irreversible so that the original data cannot be reconstructed even by the data holder?","options":["Anonymization","Tokenization","Encryption","Format-preserving substitution"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Anonymization</strong> — anonymization irreversibly removes the ability to link data to an individual so the original identity cannot be reconstructed.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Tokenization</b>: tokenization is reversible via the token vault.</span><span class='qd'><b>Encryption</b>: encryption is reversible with the correct key.</span><span class='qd'><b>Format-preserving substitution</b>: such substitution can be reversible and preserves structure, not irreversibility.</span>"},{"id":"D2-046","domain":2,"obj":"2.4","diff":"medium","q":"During discovery, a team finds regulated data copied into a developer's personal cloud drive outside sanctioned services. Which term best describes this discovery finding?","options":["Data dispersion","Shadow data / data sprawl","Data anonymization","Data tokenization"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Shadow data / data sprawl</strong> — regulated data replicated into unsanctioned locations is shadow data resulting from sprawl, a key risk that discovery is meant to surface.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Data dispersion</b>: dispersion is a deliberate resiliency technique, not accidental unsanctioned copies.</span><span class='qd'><b>Data anonymization</b>: anonymization is a protection technique, not a description of misplaced data.</span><span class='qd'><b>Data tokenization</b>: tokenization substitutes surrogate values and does not describe unsanctioned copies.</span>"},{"id":"D2-047","domain":2,"obj":"2.3","diff":"hard","q":"A stakeholder proposes using the same symmetric key for all customers' data to simplify operations. What is the strongest CCSP objection to this design?","options":["It complicates backups","It slows down hashing","A single key compromise exposes all customers' data, eliminating cryptographic tenant isolation","It prevents data classification"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>A single key compromise exposes all customers' data, eliminating cryptographic tenant isolation</strong> — sharing one key removes per-tenant crypto separation, so one compromised key breaches every customer, violating isolation and blast-radius principles.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>It complicates backups</b>: backup complexity is minor and not the core security failure.</span><span class='qd'><b>It slows down hashing</b>: hashing performance is unrelated to a shared encryption key.</span><span class='qd'><b>It prevents data classification</b>: classification is independent of how many keys are used.</span>"},{"id":"D2-048","domain":2,"obj":"2.2","diff":"easy","q":"Which storage type is characterized by long retention periods and the lowest cost per gigabyte, at the expense of higher retrieval latency?","options":["Ephemeral storage","Block/volume storage","In-memory cache","Long-term / cold archival storage"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Long-term / cold archival storage</strong> — cold archival storage offers the lowest cost for extended retention while accepting higher retrieval latency, suited to rarely accessed data.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Ephemeral storage</b>: ephemeral storage is short-lived and tied to instance life, not long retention.</span><span class='qd'><b>Block/volume storage</b>: block storage targets low-latency active workloads, not cheapest long-term retention.</span><span class='qd'><b>In-memory cache</b>: in-memory cache is the fastest and most volatile, the opposite of cold archival.</span>"},{"id":"D2-049","domain":2,"obj":"2.3","diff":"medium","q":"A cloud security team wants DLP to recognize sensitive data even when files are renamed or reformatted. Which DLP detection method is most robust against such evasion?","options":["Content-based inspection with fingerprinting/exact data match","File-extension matching","Blocking by file size","Allowing only certain IP addresses"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Content-based inspection with fingerprinting/exact data match</strong> — inspecting actual content via fingerprints or exact data matching detects sensitive data regardless of renaming or reformatting, unlike superficial attributes.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>File-extension matching</b>: extensions are trivially changed, so this is easily evaded.</span><span class='qd'><b>Blocking by file size</b>: size is not a reliable indicator of sensitive content.</span><span class='qd'><b>Allowing only certain IP addresses</b>: IP allow-listing is a network control, not content-aware DLP detection.</span>"},{"id":"D2-050","domain":2,"obj":"2.1","diff":"hard","q":"An organization insists a single 'delete' action in the Destroy phase is sufficient for a multi-tenant object store with replication and versioning. What is the most accurate CCSP caution?","options":["A single delete guarantees no recoverable copies remain","Replicas, versions, and backups may retain data, so crypto-shredding or verified deletion of all copies is needed","Deletion in the cloud is instantaneous everywhere","Only structured data needs verified deletion"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Replicas, versions, and backups may retain data, so crypto-shredding or verified deletion of all copies is needed</strong> — in dispersed, versioned, replicated cloud storage a single delete rarely removes every copy, so crypto-shredding or verified multi-copy deletion is required to truly destroy data.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A single delete guarantees no recoverable copies remain</b>: this is exactly the false assumption; versions and replicas persist.</span><span class='qd'><b>Deletion in the cloud is instantaneous everywhere</b>: propagation across replicas and backups is not instantaneous or guaranteed complete.</span><span class='qd'><b>Only structured data needs verified deletion</b>: unstructured and semi-structured data equally require verified destruction.</span>"},{"id":"D2-051","domain":2,"obj":"2.5","diff":"easy","q":"A cloud team wants a repeatable way to decide how strongly each dataset must be protected before choosing encryption, access, and retention controls. Which activity most directly produces that basis?","options":["Provisioning object storage lifecycle rules","Deploying a DLP engine at the egress point","Data classification against a policy that maps categories to handling requirements","Enabling server-side encryption on every bucket"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Data classification against a policy that maps categories to handling requirements</strong> — classification assigns each dataset a category (e.g., public, internal, confidential, restricted) whose policy dictates the controls that follow.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Provisioning object storage lifecycle rules</b>: this automates retention/tiering but presupposes a classification already decided how long and how sensitively data must be held.</span><span class='qd'><b>Deploying a DLP engine at the egress point</b>: DLP enforces classifications; it does not itself establish the sensitivity basis for controls.</span><span class='qd'><b>Enabling server-side encryption on every bucket</b>: blanket encryption is a control, not the decision framework that determines which datasets warrant which controls.</span>"},{"id":"D2-052","domain":2,"obj":"2.5","diff":"medium","q":"During a migration, an architect finds that half the classified datasets carry labels that no longer match their actual content because business use changed over years. What is the best corrective step?","options":["Delete the mislabeled datasets and recreate them","Downgrade all labels to the lowest tier to avoid over-restriction","Freeze the labels and document the drift as accepted risk","Re-run data discovery and re-classify based on current content and context"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Re-run data discovery and re-classify based on current content and context</strong> — classification is not a one-time act; drift is corrected by rediscovering and reassigning categories to reflect present sensitivity.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Delete the mislabeled datasets and recreate them</b>: destroying business data to fix a metadata problem is disproportionate and may violate retention obligations.</span><span class='qd'><b>Downgrade all labels to the lowest tier to avoid over-restriction</b>: this strips protection from data that may still be sensitive, creating exposure.</span><span class='qd'><b>Freeze the labels and document the drift as accepted risk</b>: accepting known-wrong labels leaves controls misaligned with actual sensitivity, which is not defensible.</span>"},{"id":"D2-053","domain":2,"obj":"2.5","diff":"medium","q":"A SaaS provider must apply differing controls to fields inside a single customer record (name, national ID, marketing preferences). Which classification approach fits best?","options":["Element- or attribute-level classification of individual fields","Record-level classification using the highest field's sensitivity","Container-level classification of the whole database","No classification, relying on encryption at rest for all fields"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Element- or attribute-level classification of individual fields</strong> — granular field-level classification lets each attribute receive controls proportionate to its sensitivity within one record.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Record-level classification using the highest field's sensitivity</b>: this over-protects low-sensitivity fields and can impede legitimate use of marketing data.</span><span class='qd'><b>Container-level classification of the whole database</b>: too coarse to differentiate a national ID from a preference flag in the same table.</span><span class='qd'><b>No classification, relying on encryption at rest for all fields</b>: uniform encryption ignores that fields need different access and handling rules, not just at-rest protection.</span>"},{"id":"D2-054","domain":2,"obj":"2.5","diff":"hard","q":"An organization builds a data map to support classification across multi-cloud stores. Beyond listing where data resides, what is the primary security value the map provides?","options":["It reduces the number of encryption keys needed","It reveals data flows and cross-boundary transfers so controls follow the data","It eliminates the need for a retention policy","It guarantees compliance with GDPR by default"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>It reveals data flows and cross-boundary transfers so controls follow the data</strong> — a data map's chief security value is exposing how data moves between services, regions, and jurisdictions so protection is applied wherever it lands.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>It reduces the number of encryption keys needed</b>: mapping does not consolidate keys and has no inherent effect on key count.</span><span class='qd'><b>It eliminates the need for a retention policy</b>: mapping informs retention but never removes the need to define how long data is kept.</span><span class='qd'><b>It guarantees compliance with GDPR by default</b>: a map supports compliance analysis but cannot by itself guarantee any regulatory outcome.</span>"},{"id":"D2-055","domain":2,"obj":"2.5","diff":"easy","q":"Which statement best distinguishes data labeling from data classification?","options":["Labeling defines the categories; classification applies encryption","They are identical terms with no meaningful difference","Classification decides the category; labeling is the metadata tag that records it","Labeling is a legal requirement; classification is optional"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Classification decides the category; labeling is the metadata tag that records it</strong> — classification is the decision of sensitivity level, and labeling is the act of attaching that decision as a tag so tools and people can act on it.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Labeling defines the categories; classification applies encryption</b>: reversed and inaccurate; categories come from classification policy, and encryption is a downstream control.</span><span class='qd'><b>They are identical terms with no meaningful difference</b>: they are related but distinct steps in the process.</span><span class='qd'><b>Labeling is a legal requirement; classification is optional</b>: neither framing is generally true; both are governance practices, not a fixed legal split.</span>"},{"id":"D2-056","domain":2,"obj":"2.5","diff":"medium","q":"A classification policy defines four tiers but auditors find inconsistent tier assignment across teams. What governance element most directly addresses this?","options":["A HSM to enforce key separation per tier","More frequent penetration testing","A stricter DLP block-all policy","Clear classification criteria and examples with a defined data owner accountable for decisions"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Clear classification criteria and examples with a defined data owner accountable for decisions</strong> — inconsistency comes from ambiguous criteria and unclear accountability; explicit criteria plus a responsible data owner drives consistent assignment.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A HSM to enforce key separation per tier</b>: an HSM protects keys but does nothing to make humans assign tiers consistently.</span><span class='qd'><b>More frequent penetration testing</b>: pen testing evaluates exploitability, not classification consistency.</span><span class='qd'><b>A stricter DLP block-all policy</b>: blocking everything harms operations and still relies on correct classifications to be meaningful.</span>"},{"id":"D2-057","domain":2,"obj":"2.5","diff":"hard","q":"An analyst proposes classifying data automatically at ingestion using content inspection. What is the most significant residual risk the security architect should flag?","options":["Context-dependent sensitivity may be missed, causing under-classification","Automated inspection cannot run in the cloud","It always over-classifies, making data unusable","It removes the need for any data owner involvement"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Context-dependent sensitivity may be missed, causing under-classification</strong> — pattern-based inspection can miss data whose sensitivity depends on business context rather than obvious patterns, leading to under-classification and exposure.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Automated inspection cannot run in the cloud</b>: cloud-native classification services exist and run routinely; this is false.</span><span class='qd'><b>It always over-classifies, making data unusable</b>: automation can err either way; it does not invariably over-classify.</span><span class='qd'><b>It removes the need for any data owner involvement</b>: owners remain accountable to validate and tune automated results, so this is not the residual risk to flag.</span>"},{"id":"D2-058","domain":2,"obj":"2.5","diff":"medium","q":"A company mapping its data discovers a copy of a restricted dataset replicated to an analytics store in another region for BI. What should classification governance require next?","options":["Immediately delete the analytics copy without review","Ensure the copy inherits the source's classification and equivalent controls, and validate the transfer is authorized","Reclassify the source down to match the analytics store","Ignore it because BI stores are exempt"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Ensure the copy inherits the source's classification and equivalent controls, and validate the transfer is authorized</strong> — classification travels with the data; a replicated restricted dataset must retain its category and controls and the cross-region flow must be authorized.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Immediately delete the analytics copy without review</b>: deletion may destroy a sanctioned, business-needed copy; review comes first.</span><span class='qd'><b>Reclassify the source down to match the analytics store</b>: lowering the source's classification to fit a weaker store inverts the correct direction and removes protection.</span><span class='qd'><b>Ignore it because BI stores are exempt</b>: no store is exempt from carrying the data's classification and controls.</span>"},{"id":"D2-059","domain":2,"obj":"2.5","diff":"easy","q":"What is the primary purpose of a data classification policy in a cloud environment?","options":["To list every user who can access a system","To specify the cloud provider's SLA uptime targets","To define categories of sensitivity and the required handling for each","To document the network topology"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>To define categories of sensitivity and the required handling for each</strong> — the policy sets the sensitivity tiers and the handling, storage, and protection rules that each tier mandates.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>To list every user who can access a system</b>: that is an access control or IAM artifact, not a classification policy.</span><span class='qd'><b>To specify the cloud provider's SLA uptime targets</b>: SLAs are contractual availability terms, unrelated to sensitivity categories.</span><span class='qd'><b>To document the network topology</b>: topology is an architecture artifact, not a classification policy.</span>"},{"id":"D2-060","domain":2,"obj":"2.5","diff":"hard","q":"A regulated firm wants labels to drive automated enforcement (DLP, IRM, retention). Which labeling design choice best enables this?","options":["Human-readable labels stored only in a wiki","Color-coded printouts attached to server racks","A quarterly spreadsheet of dataset names","Machine-readable metadata tags bound to the data and consumable by controls"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Machine-readable metadata tags bound to the data and consumable by controls</strong> — for automation, labels must be structured metadata that travels with the data and that DLP, IRM, and lifecycle engines can read and act on.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Human-readable labels stored only in a wiki</b>: a wiki is disconnected from the data and cannot drive automated enforcement.</span><span class='qd'><b>Color-coded printouts attached to server racks</b>: physical tags cannot be consumed by cloud data controls.</span><span class='qd'><b>A quarterly spreadsheet of dataset names</b>: a periodic list is neither bound to the data nor consumable in real time by enforcement engines.</span>"},{"id":"D2-061","domain":2,"obj":"2.6","diff":"easy","q":"What is the core objective of Information Rights Management (IRM) applied to a document?","options":["To enforce usage rights (view, edit, print, forward) that persist with the file wherever it travels","To back up the document to a second region","To compress the file to save storage","To index the file for search"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>To enforce usage rights (view, edit, print, forward) that persist with the file wherever it travels</strong> — IRM embeds and enforces per-object usage policy so protection follows the data outside the origin store.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>To back up the document to a second region</b>: that is replication or backup, not rights enforcement.</span><span class='qd'><b>To compress the file to save storage</b>: compression addresses size, not access rights.</span><span class='qd'><b>To index the file for search</b>: indexing aids discovery, not usage-rights enforcement.</span>"},{"id":"D2-062","domain":2,"obj":"2.6","diff":"medium","q":"A partner leaves a joint project and their access to shared IRM-protected files must end immediately, even for copies already on their laptop. Which IRM capability achieves this?","options":["At-rest encryption on the source repository","Certificate/license revocation so the policy server denies future decryption","A firewall rule blocking the partner's IP","Deleting the files from the shared repository"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Certificate/license revocation so the policy server denies future decryption</strong> — IRM ties access to issued rights; revoking the partner's certificate or license means their local copies can no longer be authorized to open, even offline copies once they re-check.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>At-rest encryption on the source repository</b>: it protects the source store but does nothing about copies already on the laptop.</span><span class='qd'><b>A firewall rule blocking the partner's IP</b>: IP blocking can be bypassed and does not revoke rights embedded in the files.</span><span class='qd'><b>Deleting the files from the shared repository</b>: deleting the source does not remove or de-authorize the copies the partner already holds.</span>"},{"id":"D2-063","domain":2,"obj":"2.6","diff":"medium","q":"An IRM deployment requires that recipients outside the organization can open protected files. What is the key provisioning consideration?","options":["Recipients must install the cloud provider's billing agent","The files must be moved to public storage","Recipients must be issued or federated identities and rights the policy server can validate","IRM must be disabled for external users"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Recipients must be issued or federated identities and rights the policy server can validate</strong> — external recipients need a provisioned or federated identity plus granted rights so the IRM policy server can authenticate them and authorize decryption.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Recipients must install the cloud provider's billing agent</b>: billing agents are unrelated to rights validation.</span><span class='qd'><b>The files must be moved to public storage</b>: public storage removes protection and contradicts IRM's purpose.</span><span class='qd'><b>IRM must be disabled for external users</b>: disabling IRM defeats the goal of protecting files shared externally.</span>"},{"id":"D2-064","domain":2,"obj":"2.6","diff":"hard","q":"A CISO worries that IRM introduces a single point of failure. Which architectural concern is most valid and must be mitigated?","options":["IRM makes files larger, exhausting storage","IRM prevents any encryption of data at rest","IRM cannot integrate with identity providers","Availability of the policy/licensing server determines whether legitimate users can open protected content"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Availability of the policy/licensing server determines whether legitimate users can open protected content</strong> — because decryption depends on the IRM policy server issuing licenses, its availability is a genuine dependency that must be made resilient.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>IRM makes files larger, exhausting storage</b>: overhead is minor and not the architectural single-point-of-failure concern.</span><span class='qd'><b>IRM prevents any encryption of data at rest</b>: IRM commonly relies on encryption, not the opposite.</span><span class='qd'><b>IRM cannot integrate with identity providers</b>: modern IRM integrates with IdPs; this is false and not the concern.</span>"},{"id":"D2-065","domain":2,"obj":"2.6","diff":"medium","q":"Which access model does IRM most closely implement when it binds a specific set of allowed actions to each user for each protected object?","options":["Fine-grained, per-object usage rights (a form of attribute/rights-based control)","Network segmentation","Time-based one-time passwords","Physical badge access"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Fine-grained, per-object usage rights (a form of attribute/rights-based control)</strong> — IRM enforces which actions each identity may perform on each object, a granular rights model that persists with the data.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Network segmentation</b>: segmentation controls network reachability, not per-object document actions.</span><span class='qd'><b>Time-based one-time passwords</b>: TOTP is an authentication factor, not a usage-rights model.</span><span class='qd'><b>Physical badge access</b>: badges govern facility entry, unrelated to document usage rights.</span>"},{"id":"D2-066","domain":2,"obj":"2.6","diff":"easy","q":"An IRM system issues certificates to authorized users. What operational process must accompany issuance to keep the system secure over time?","options":["Doubling the key length every month","Certificate revocation for users who lose authorization","Publishing all certificates publicly","Disabling logging to improve performance"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Certificate revocation for users who lose authorization</strong> — issuance must be paired with timely revocation so departed or de-authorized users lose the ability to open protected content.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Doubling the key length every month</b>: arbitrary key-length changes are unnecessary and operationally harmful.</span><span class='qd'><b>Publishing all certificates publicly</b>: exposing certificates broadly undermines the trust model.</span><span class='qd'><b>Disabling logging to improve performance</b>: removing logs weakens accountability and auditability of rights use.</span>"},{"id":"D2-067","domain":2,"obj":"2.6","diff":"hard","q":"A media company distributes IRM-protected content to consumers who must view it offline for limited periods. Which IRM feature best supports this while limiting exposure?","options":["Perpetual offline access with no re-check","Storing the decryption key inside the file in plaintext","Time-bounded licenses that expire and require re-authorization","Disabling all offline use"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Time-bounded licenses that expire and require re-authorization</strong> — issuing licenses valid for a limited window lets consumers view offline while forcing periodic re-authorization to contain exposure if access should end.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Perpetual offline access with no re-check</b>: permanent offline rights remove the ability to revoke, maximizing exposure.</span><span class='qd'><b>Storing the decryption key inside the file in plaintext</b>: embedding a plaintext key defeats the protection entirely.</span><span class='qd'><b>Disabling all offline use</b>: this fails the stated requirement that consumers view offline.</span>"},{"id":"D2-068","domain":2,"obj":"2.6","diff":"medium","q":"An organization wants IRM policies to apply automatically based on how documents are classified. What integration best achieves this?","options":["Require users to manually pick IRM settings each time they save","Apply IRM only to files over 10 MB","Replace classification labels with IRM entirely","Bind IRM policy templates to classification labels so labeling triggers rights enforcement"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Bind IRM policy templates to classification labels so labeling triggers rights enforcement</strong> — mapping IRM templates to classification labels makes protection automatic and consistent whenever a label is applied.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Require users to manually pick IRM settings each time they save</b>: manual selection is inconsistent and error-prone, the problem automation solves.</span><span class='qd'><b>Apply IRM only to files over 10 MB</b>: size is irrelevant to sensitivity and would miss small confidential files.</span><span class='qd'><b>Replace classification labels with IRM entirely</b>: IRM enforces policy; it does not substitute for classifying data in the first place.</span>"},{"id":"D2-069","domain":2,"obj":"2.6","diff":"medium","q":"A security review notes that IRM-protected files can still be photographed on screen or retyped. How should the architect frame this limitation?","options":["IRM raises the effort and auditability of misuse but cannot stop analog capture; layer with awareness and monitoring","It proves IRM is worthless and should be removed","IRM should be reconfigured to block screenshots at the hardware level everywhere","This is a defect the vendor must patch to make capture impossible"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>IRM raises the effort and auditability of misuse but cannot stop analog capture; layer with awareness and monitoring</strong> — IRM is a strong deterrent and enforcement layer but the analog hole is inherent, so it is complemented by training and monitoring rather than expected to be absolute.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>It proves IRM is worthless and should be removed</b>: IRM still meaningfully controls and audits digital use; abandoning it overreacts.</span><span class='qd'><b>IRM should be reconfigured to block screenshots at the hardware level everywhere</b>: universal hardware screenshot blocking is impractical and still cannot stop a camera.</span><span class='qd'><b>This is a defect the vendor must patch to make capture impossible</b>: analog capture is a fundamental limit no vendor patch can eliminate.</span>"},{"id":"D2-070","domain":2,"obj":"2.6","diff":"hard","q":"In a cloud collaboration platform, IRM must enforce that only members of a dynamic group can edit a file, with membership changing daily. Which approach keeps enforcement current?","options":["Hard-code the member list into each file at creation","Evaluate rights at access time against a live directory/attribute source","Email the file to current members each morning","Re-encrypt every file nightly with a new static ACL"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Evaluate rights at access time against a live directory/attribute source</strong> — checking group membership dynamically at each access ensures enforcement reflects current membership without reprocessing files.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Hard-code the member list into each file at creation</b>: a baked-in list goes stale immediately as membership changes.</span><span class='qd'><b>Email the file to current members each morning</b>: distributing copies loses control and does not enforce edit rights.</span><span class='qd'><b>Re-encrypt every file nightly with a new static ACL</b>: nightly static ACLs still lag intraday changes and are operationally heavy.</span>"},{"id":"D2-071","domain":2,"obj":"2.7","diff":"easy","q":"What does a data retention policy primarily specify?","options":["Which encryption algorithm to use","The IP addresses allowed to access storage","How long each category of data must be kept and when it may or must be disposed of","The number of backups stored per week"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>How long each category of data must be kept and when it may or must be disposed of</strong> — a retention policy defines retention periods per data category and the point at which data is deleted or archived.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Which encryption algorithm to use</b>: algorithm choice is a cryptographic control, not a retention decision.</span><span class='qd'><b>The IP addresses allowed to access storage</b>: that is a network access control, unrelated to retention duration.</span><span class='qd'><b>The number of backups stored per week</b>: backup frequency is an operational detail distinct from retention-period policy.</span>"},{"id":"D2-072","domain":2,"obj":"2.7","diff":"medium","q":"A tenant using a multi-tenant SaaS wants assurance that deleted records are unrecoverable, but the provider controls the physical media shared across tenants. Which deletion method is most appropriate?","options":["Physical shredding of the drives","Degaussing the storage array","Overwriting each sector seven times","Cryptographic erasure by destroying the tenant's encryption keys"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Cryptographic erasure by destroying the tenant's encryption keys</strong> — in shared multi-tenant media, crypto-shredding renders a tenant's data unrecoverable by destroying the keys, without disturbing other tenants' data.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Physical shredding of the drives</b>: destroying shared media would also destroy other tenants' data and is not tenant-selectable.</span><span class='qd'><b>Degaussing the storage array</b>: degaussing affects the whole medium and is impossible to scope to one tenant in shared storage.</span><span class='qd'><b>Overwriting each sector seven times</b>: tenants typically cannot address physical sectors in abstracted cloud storage, and overwrite guarantees are unreliable there.</span>"},{"id":"D2-073","domain":2,"obj":"2.7","diff":"medium","q":"Legal counsel places a litigation hold on certain customer records. The retention schedule says those records are due for automated deletion tomorrow. What must happen?","options":["The legal hold suspends deletion for the affected records until the hold is lifted","Deletion proceeds as scheduled to honor retention","The records are archived to cold storage and then deleted","The retention period is shortened to delete immediately"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>The legal hold suspends deletion for the affected records until the hold is lifted</strong> — legal hold overrides routine retention/deletion so relevant data is preserved for litigation or investigation.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Deletion proceeds as scheduled to honor retention</b>: destroying data under hold can constitute spoliation and legal liability.</span><span class='qd'><b>The records are archived to cold storage and then deleted</b>: eventual deletion still destroys held evidence and violates the hold.</span><span class='qd'><b>The retention period is shortened to delete immediately</b>: accelerating deletion of held data is exactly what a hold forbids.</span>"},{"id":"D2-074","domain":2,"obj":"2.7","diff":"hard","q":"An organization crypto-shreds a dataset by destroying its keys, but discovers backups of that data were encrypted under a different key set that still exists. What is the correct conclusion?","options":["The data is fully destroyed because the primary keys are gone","The data remains recoverable until all key sets protecting all copies are destroyed","Crypto-shredding never works and should be abandoned","Only the primary copy needs its key destroyed for compliance"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>The data remains recoverable until all key sets protecting all copies are destroyed</strong> — crypto-shredding only assures destruction when every copy's protecting key is destroyed; surviving keys for backups leave the data recoverable.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The data is fully destroyed because the primary keys are gone</b>: backups under other keys remain readable, so destruction is incomplete.</span><span class='qd'><b>Crypto-shredding never works and should be abandoned</b>: it works when applied to all key sets; the gap is process, not the technique.</span><span class='qd'><b>Only the primary copy needs its key destroyed for compliance</b>: leaving recoverable backups fails a defensible-deletion standard.</span>"},{"id":"D2-075","domain":2,"obj":"2.7","diff":"easy","q":"What is the primary purpose of archiving data rather than deleting it?","options":["To permanently destroy data no longer needed","To speed up transactional database queries","To retain data that is infrequently accessed but must be kept for compliance or future use","To bypass retention requirements"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>To retain data that is infrequently accessed but must be kept for compliance or future use</strong> — archiving moves rarely used data to lower-cost, long-term storage while preserving it for regulatory or business needs.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>To permanently destroy data no longer needed</b>: that describes deletion, the opposite of archiving.</span><span class='qd'><b>To speed up transactional database queries</b>: query performance tuning is unrelated to the purpose of archiving.</span><span class='qd'><b>To bypass retention requirements</b>: archiving fulfills retention requirements rather than circumventing them.</span>"},{"id":"D2-076","domain":2,"obj":"2.7","diff":"medium","q":"An archiving strategy stores encrypted data for 10 years. Which risk most threatens the ability to actually read the archive at year 10?","options":["The data will be over-classified","The archive will use too little storage","Retention periods cannot exceed one year","Loss of the decryption keys or obsolescence of the format/media"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Loss of the decryption keys or obsolescence of the format/media</strong> — long-term archives are threatened by losing the keys needed to decrypt and by format or media obsolescence that makes the data unreadable.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The data will be over-classified</b>: classification level does not prevent reading a properly retained archive.</span><span class='qd'><b>The archive will use too little storage</b>: storage size is not what jeopardizes future readability.</span><span class='qd'><b>Retention periods cannot exceed one year</b>: there is no such limit; multi-year retention is routine.</span>"},{"id":"D2-077","domain":2,"obj":"2.7","diff":"hard","q":"A regulator requires that certain records be both retained for seven years and provably deleted at the end. Which combination best satisfies both ends of the lifecycle?","options":["Immutable/WORM storage for the retention window plus verifiable crypto-shredding at expiry","Standard mutable storage with manual deletion when someone remembers","Public object storage with lifecycle auto-tiering only","Local laptop storage with periodic backups"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Immutable/WORM storage for the retention window plus verifiable crypto-shredding at expiry</strong> — WORM guarantees the record cannot be altered or prematurely deleted during retention, and crypto-shredding at expiry provides defensible, verifiable destruction.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Standard mutable storage with manual deletion when someone remembers</b>: mutable storage risks tampering and manual deletion is not defensible or reliable.</span><span class='qd'><b>Public object storage with lifecycle auto-tiering only</b>: tiering moves data between classes but neither guarantees immutability nor provable destruction, and public exposure is inappropriate.</span><span class='qd'><b>Local laptop storage with periodic backups</b>: laptops fail immutability, durability, and provable-deletion requirements entirely.</span>"},{"id":"D2-078","domain":2,"obj":"2.7","diff":"medium","q":"After a contract ends, a cloud customer requests deletion of all their data. What must the provider's deletion procedure also address to be complete?","options":["Only the production copy in the primary region","All copies including backups, replicas, caches, and logs, within contractually defined timeframes","Just the metadata, leaving the objects intact","The customer's on-premises copies only"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>All copies including backups, replicas, caches, and logs, within contractually defined timeframes</strong> — complete deletion must reach every derivative copy the provider holds, bounded by the contract's stated timeframes.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Only the production copy in the primary region</b>: leaving replicas and backups means the data still exists and deletion is incomplete.</span><span class='qd'><b>Just the metadata, leaving the objects intact</b>: removing metadata while retaining the objects does not delete the data.</span><span class='qd'><b>The customer's on-premises copies only</b>: the provider controls the cloud copies; on-prem is the customer's responsibility, not the provider's deletion scope.</span>"},{"id":"D2-079","domain":2,"obj":"2.7","diff":"easy","q":"Which control best prevents data from being deleted before its required retention period ends?","options":["A DLP egress rule","A stronger password policy","WORM (write-once-read-many) or retention-lock on the storage","A faster CPU tier"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>WORM (write-once-read-many) or retention-lock on the storage</strong> — WORM/retention-lock enforces that data cannot be modified or deleted until the retention period expires.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A DLP egress rule</b>: DLP inspects data leaving the environment; it does not prevent premature deletion.</span><span class='qd'><b>A stronger password policy</b>: passwords address authentication, not retention enforcement.</span><span class='qd'><b>A faster CPU tier</b>: compute performance is irrelevant to retention protection.</span>"},{"id":"D2-080","domain":2,"obj":"2.7","diff":"hard","q":"An organization sets a single blanket retention period of 25 years for all data to simplify governance. What is the strongest objection from a privacy and risk standpoint?","options":["It saves too much money","Long retention improves query speed","It guarantees compliance with every regulation","Over-retention increases breach exposure and may violate data-minimization and privacy laws"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Over-retention increases breach exposure and may violate data-minimization and privacy laws</strong> — keeping data longer than needed expands the attack surface and can breach minimization principles in privacy regimes like GDPR.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>It saves too much money</b>: blanket long retention typically raises storage and risk costs, not savings.</span><span class='qd'><b>Long retention improves query speed</b>: retention duration does not improve performance and is irrelevant to the objection.</span><span class='qd'><b>It guarantees compliance with every regulation</b>: uniform long retention can itself breach minimization rules, so it guarantees nothing.</span>"},{"id":"D2-081","domain":2,"obj":"2.7","diff":"medium","q":"A data-destruction procedure must be defensible in court. Which artifact most strengthens that defensibility?","options":["A certificate of destruction and logged evidence tying the method, scope, and timestamp to policy","A screenshot of the storage console","An email saying the data was probably deleted","The invoice for the storage service"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>A certificate of destruction and logged evidence tying the method, scope, and timestamp to policy</strong> — defensible destruction is proven with formal certificates and logs documenting what was destroyed, how, when, and under which policy.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A screenshot of the storage console</b>: a screenshot is weak, easily disputed evidence lacking method and chain detail.</span><span class='qd'><b>An email saying the data was probably deleted</b>: hedged, informal assertions do not establish defensible destruction.</span><span class='qd'><b>The invoice for the storage service</b>: billing records say nothing about destruction of specific data.</span>"},{"id":"D2-082","domain":2,"obj":"2.7","diff":"medium","q":"A cloud archive uses lifecycle rules to transition objects from hot to cold to deep-archive tiers. What must the retention policy ensure about this automation?","options":["That objects are deleted as soon as they enter cold storage","That objects tier down only after their required retention and access needs are met, and are not deleted early","That all objects stay in the hot tier forever","That tiering replaces the need for any legal hold mechanism"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>That objects tier down only after their required retention and access needs are met, and are not deleted early</strong> — lifecycle automation must respect retention: move to cheaper tiers appropriately, and never delete before the retention period or a hold allows.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>That objects are deleted as soon as they enter cold storage</b>: cold storage is for retention, not immediate deletion.</span><span class='qd'><b>That all objects stay in the hot tier forever</b>: this negates the cost purpose of tiering and is not a retention requirement.</span><span class='qd'><b>That tiering replaces the need for any legal hold mechanism</b>: tiering is orthogonal to holds; holds must still be able to suspend deletion.</span>"},{"id":"D2-083","domain":2,"obj":"2.8","diff":"easy","q":"What is the primary goal of auditability for data events in the cloud?","options":["To reduce storage costs","To encrypt data in transit","To provide a reliable record of who did what, when, and from where","To load-balance application traffic"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>To provide a reliable record of who did what, when, and from where</strong> — auditability captures data-event details supporting accountability, investigation, and non-repudiation.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>To reduce storage costs</b>: logging generally adds storage; cost reduction is not its goal.</span><span class='qd'><b>To encrypt data in transit</b>: encryption is a confidentiality control, not the purpose of auditability.</span><span class='qd'><b>To load-balance application traffic</b>: load balancing is a performance function unrelated to audit records.</span>"},{"id":"D2-084","domain":2,"obj":"2.8","diff":"medium","q":"An incident responder needs to attribute a data-exfiltration event to a specific user session. Which combination of log attributes is most useful?","options":["CPU temperature and fan speed","Only the total byte count transferred","The storage bucket's monthly cost","Identity, source IP, geolocation, timestamp, and action performed"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Identity, source IP, geolocation, timestamp, and action performed</strong> — attribution relies on event attributes that tie an identity, location, time, and specific action together to reconstruct the session.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>CPU temperature and fan speed</b>: hardware telemetry does not attribute data actions to a user.</span><span class='qd'><b>Only the total byte count transferred</b>: volume alone cannot identify who acted or from where.</span><span class='qd'><b>The storage bucket's monthly cost</b>: billing data is irrelevant to attributing an event to a session.</span>"},{"id":"D2-085","domain":2,"obj":"2.8","diff":"medium","q":"To preserve non-repudiation for critical data events, which log-handling practice is most important?","options":["Protect log integrity with tamper-evidence, immutability, and restricted access","Allow administrators to edit logs to correct errors","Store logs on the same server that generated them only","Delete logs weekly to save space"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Protect log integrity with tamper-evidence, immutability, and restricted access</strong> — non-repudiation depends on logs that cannot be altered undetectably, so integrity protection and access restriction are essential.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Allow administrators to edit logs to correct errors</b>: editable logs destroy non-repudiation because entries could be forged or altered.</span><span class='qd'><b>Store logs on the same server that generated them only</b>: co-locating logs lets an attacker who compromises the host also tamper with the evidence.</span><span class='qd'><b>Delete logs weekly to save space</b>: premature deletion removes the evidence needed for accountability.</span>"},{"id":"D2-086","domain":2,"obj":"2.8","diff":"hard","q":"An investigation may lead to prosecution, so collected cloud logs must be admissible. Which practice most directly supports evidentiary chain of custody?","options":["Emailing log files to whoever needs them","Documenting each transfer and handler of the evidence with integrity hashes from collection onward","Compressing logs to a proprietary format","Keeping only a printed summary of the logs"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Documenting each transfer and handler of the evidence with integrity hashes from collection onward</strong> — chain of custody requires a documented, hash-verified record of every custodian and handoff so the evidence's integrity is demonstrable in court.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Emailing log files to whoever needs them</b>: uncontrolled distribution breaks custody tracking and integrity assurance.</span><span class='qd'><b>Compressing logs to a proprietary format</b>: format choice does not establish custody and may hinder verification.</span><span class='qd'><b>Keeping only a printed summary of the logs</b>: a summary is not the original evidence and cannot be integrity-verified.</span>"},{"id":"D2-087","domain":2,"obj":"2.8","diff":"easy","q":"Which system best aggregates and correlates data-event logs from many cloud services for analysis and alerting?","options":["A load balancer","A content delivery network","A SIEM (Security Information and Event Management) platform","A relational database backup tool"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>A SIEM (Security Information and Event Management) platform</strong> — a SIEM centralizes, correlates, and analyzes logs across sources to detect and alert on suspicious data events.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>A load balancer</b>: it distributes traffic; it does not correlate security events.</span><span class='qd'><b>A content delivery network</b>: a CDN caches and delivers content, not log correlation.</span><span class='qd'><b>A relational database backup tool</b>: backups protect data but do not aggregate or analyze event logs.</span>"},{"id":"D2-088","domain":2,"obj":"2.8","diff":"medium","q":"A cloud audit reveals that log timestamps from different services disagree by minutes, complicating event correlation. What is the best remedy?","options":["Disable logging on the slower services","Manually adjust timestamps after the fact","Accept the drift as unavoidable in the cloud","Synchronize all sources to a common, trusted time reference (e.g., NTP) and normalize to UTC"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Synchronize all sources to a common, trusted time reference (e.g., NTP) and normalize to UTC</strong> — accurate correlation requires consistent, synchronized time across sources, achieved with a trusted time source and normalized time zone.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Disable logging on the slower services</b>: removing logs loses visibility rather than fixing time alignment.</span><span class='qd'><b>Manually adjust timestamps after the fact</b>: manual edits are error-prone and undermine log integrity.</span><span class='qd'><b>Accept the drift as unavoidable in the cloud</b>: time synchronization is a standard, achievable practice, so drift is not unavoidable.</span>"},{"id":"D2-089","domain":2,"obj":"2.8","diff":"hard","q":"A tenant relies on the provider's audit logs but cannot independently verify their completeness. Which control best addresses this trust gap in a shared-responsibility model?","options":["Obtain the provider's independent audit attestation (e.g., SOC 2) covering logging controls and stream logs to a tenant-controlled store","Assume the provider logs are always complete","Turn off all provider logging and rely only on application logs","Store logs only in the provider's default location"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Obtain the provider's independent audit attestation (e.g., SOC 2) covering logging controls and stream logs to a tenant-controlled store</strong> — combining third-party assurance over the provider's logging with a tenant-owned copy of the logs addresses both trust and independent retention.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Assume the provider logs are always complete</b>: unverified assumption is exactly the trust gap that must be closed.</span><span class='qd'><b>Turn off all provider logging and rely only on application logs</b>: disabling provider logs loses infrastructure-layer visibility the tenant cannot reproduce.</span><span class='qd'><b>Store logs only in the provider's default location</b>: sole reliance on provider-controlled storage leaves the tenant unable to preserve independent evidence.</span>"},{"id":"D2-090","domain":2,"obj":"2.8","diff":"medium","q":"Which principle ensures that a user cannot credibly deny having performed a logged data action?","options":["Availability","Non-repudiation","Elasticity","Multi-tenancy"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Non-repudiation</strong> — non-repudiation binds actions to identities with integrity-protected evidence so a party cannot plausibly deny the action.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Availability</b>: availability concerns access to systems, not proof of who acted.</span><span class='qd'><b>Elasticity</b>: elasticity is a scaling characteristic unrelated to accountability.</span><span class='qd'><b>Multi-tenancy</b>: multi-tenancy describes shared infrastructure, not denial of actions.</span>"},{"id":"D2-091","domain":2,"obj":"2.8","diff":"hard","q":"Log volume from a large cloud estate is overwhelming analysts with noise. Which approach best preserves auditability while improving signal?","options":["Stop collecting logs from noisy sources","Only keep alerts and discard all raw logs immediately","Define event sources and attributes to capture by risk, apply correlation/filtering in the SIEM, and retain raw logs for forensics","Randomly sample 1% of all events"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Define event sources and attributes to capture by risk, apply correlation/filtering in the SIEM, and retain raw logs for forensics</strong> — a risk-driven collection scope with SIEM correlation reduces noise for analysts while raw retention preserves full auditability and forensic value.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Stop collecting logs from noisy sources</b>: dropping whole sources creates blind spots, harming auditability.</span><span class='qd'><b>Only keep alerts and discard all raw logs immediately</b>: discarding raw logs destroys the evidence needed for later investigation.</span><span class='qd'><b>Randomly sample 1% of all events</b>: sampling loses most events and cannot support reliable forensics or attribution.</span>"},{"id":"D2-092","domain":2,"obj":"2.5","diff":"medium","q":"A data-mapping exercise must feed both classification and privacy programs. Which additional attribute, beyond location and sensitivity, is most valuable to capture per dataset?","options":["The marketing budget for the dataset","The color theme of the dashboard","The developer who wrote the ingestion code","Data subject/owner, lawful basis or purpose, and jurisdiction"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Data subject/owner, lawful basis or purpose, and jurisdiction</strong> — capturing who the data concerns, why it is processed, and where it is subject to law lets the map serve both classification and privacy compliance.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The marketing budget for the dataset</b>: budget figures do not inform classification or privacy handling.</span><span class='qd'><b>The color theme of the dashboard</b>: presentation styling is irrelevant to data governance.</span><span class='qd'><b>The developer who wrote the ingestion code</b>: authorship is trivia here and does not drive sensitivity or lawful-basis decisions.</span>"},{"id":"D2-093","domain":2,"obj":"2.6","diff":"medium","q":"An enterprise wants IRM protection to remain effective even after files leave the corporate cloud tenancy and are stored on unmanaged devices. Which property makes this possible?","options":["IRM enforcement is embedded with the data and validated against a policy server at access time","The files must be stored only on managed devices","The unmanaged devices must join the corporate domain first","IRM only works inside the corporate network"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>IRM enforcement is embedded with the data and validated against a policy server at access time</strong> — because rights travel with the file and are checked at each access, protection persists on unmanaged devices as long as the policy server can be consulted.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>The files must be stored only on managed devices</b>: this defeats the requirement that protection survive on unmanaged devices.</span><span class='qd'><b>The unmanaged devices must join the corporate domain first</b>: domain join is not required for IRM to enforce embedded rights.</span><span class='qd'><b>IRM only works inside the corporate network</b>: modern IRM works beyond the network perimeter, which is its point.</span>"},{"id":"D2-094","domain":2,"obj":"2.7","diff":"medium","q":"A backup retention rule keeps daily backups for 35 days. A customer invokes their right to erasure for specific personal data. What is the correct handling of that data within backups?","options":["Ignore backups since erasure applies only to production","Document that the data is isolated in backups and will be purged on the normal rotation, protected and not restored to production in the interim","Immediately restore all backups to delete the record, then re-back-up","Extend backup retention to keep evidence of the request"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Document that the data is isolated in backups and will be purged on the normal rotation, protected and not restored to production in the interim</strong> — a defensible approach documents that backup copies age out on schedule while ensuring the data is not reintroduced to production, balancing erasure duties with backup realities.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Ignore backups since erasure applies only to production</b>: erasure obligations extend to copies, so backups cannot simply be ignored.</span><span class='qd'><b>Immediately restore all backups to delete the record, then re-back-up</b>: mass restoration is risky, disruptive, and can reintroduce other erased or stale data.</span><span class='qd'><b>Extend backup retention to keep evidence of the request</b>: prolonging retention of the very data to be erased worsens the exposure and contradicts the request.</span>"},{"id":"D2-095","domain":2,"obj":"2.8","diff":"medium","q":"An auditor asks how the cloud team demonstrates accountability for privileged access to sensitive datasets. Which practice best answers this?","options":["Shared admin accounts with a common password","Disabling MFA to simplify admin logins","Individual named accounts with logged, attributable actions and periodic access reviews","Rotating a single API key among the whole team"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Individual named accounts with logged, attributable actions and periodic access reviews</strong> — accountability requires that each privileged action trace to a unique identity, with logs and reviews evidencing appropriate access.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Shared admin accounts with a common password</b>: shared accounts destroy attribution, the core of accountability.</span><span class='qd'><b>Disabling MFA to simplify admin logins</b>: weakening authentication reduces assurance that the logged identity is genuine.</span><span class='qd'><b>Rotating a single API key among the whole team</b>: a shared key cannot attribute actions to an individual.</span>"},{"id":"D2-096","domain":2,"obj":"2.5","diff":"hard","q":"A firm classifies data at creation but finds that derived analytics outputs sometimes reveal sensitive information not present in any single source (mosaic effect). How should classification governance respond?","options":["Classify only raw inputs and ignore derived outputs","Always classify outputs at the lowest input tier","Prohibit all analytics to avoid the problem","Assess and classify derived/aggregated outputs on their own merits, potentially higher than any single input"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Assess and classify derived/aggregated outputs on their own merits, potentially higher than any single input</strong> — aggregation can create sensitivity greater than its parts, so outputs must be independently classified rather than inheriting a lower input tier.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Classify only raw inputs and ignore derived outputs</b>: ignoring outputs leaves the mosaic-created sensitivity unprotected.</span><span class='qd'><b>Always classify outputs at the lowest input tier</b>: this understates aggregated sensitivity and creates exposure.</span><span class='qd'><b>Prohibit all analytics to avoid the problem</b>: banning analytics is disproportionate and sacrifices legitimate business value.</span>"},{"id":"D2-097","domain":2,"obj":"2.7","diff":"hard","q":"A cloud provider offers only logical deletion (marking data deleted) with eventual physical overwrite on an unknown schedule. For highly sensitive tenant data, what is the most defensible tenant strategy?","options":["Encrypt data client-side with tenant-held keys so destroying the keys renders logically deleted data unrecoverable","Rely entirely on the provider's logical deletion","Store the data unencrypted for easier deletion","Request the provider to email confirmation of physical overwrite"],"answer":0,"explain":"<strong>Encrypt data client-side with tenant-held keys so destroying the keys renders logically deleted data unrecoverable</strong> — tenant-controlled client-side encryption lets crypto-shredding guarantee unrecoverability regardless of the provider's opaque physical-deletion timing.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Rely entirely on the provider's logical deletion</b>: logical deletion leaves recoverable data until an unknown overwrite, which is not defensible for sensitive data.</span><span class='qd'><b>Store the data unencrypted for easier deletion</b>: unencrypted storage removes the very control that would make deletion assured and worsens exposure.</span><span class='qd'><b>Request the provider to email confirmation of physical overwrite</b>: an email about an unknown schedule provides no timely, verifiable destruction assurance.</span>"},{"id":"D2-098","domain":2,"obj":"2.8","diff":"medium","q":"A compliance team must retain audit logs longer than the operational SIEM keeps them. What is the best design?","options":["Delete logs when the SIEM ages them out","Forward logs to durable, access-controlled long-term storage (e.g., immutable archive) meeting the retention requirement","Keep logs only on analyst laptops","Print the logs and file them physically"],"answer":1,"explain":"<strong>Forward logs to durable, access-controlled long-term storage (e.g., immutable archive) meeting the retention requirement</strong> — audit logs needed beyond SIEM hot retention should be shipped to durable, immutable, access-controlled archives sized to the mandated retention period.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Delete logs when the SIEM ages them out</b>: deleting at SIEM expiry fails the longer retention requirement.</span><span class='qd'><b>Keep logs only on analyst laptops</b>: laptops lack durability, access control, and immutability for audit evidence.</span><span class='qd'><b>Print the logs and file them physically</b>: printouts are unsearchable, hard to integrity-verify, and impractical at scale.</span>"},{"id":"D2-099","domain":2,"obj":"2.6","diff":"medium","q":"Which scenario is the clearest fit for IRM rather than storage-level encryption alone?","options":["Protecting data only while it sits in one encrypted bucket","Encrypting a database's underlying volumes","Ensuring a downloaded confidential report cannot be forwarded or printed by recipients","Encrypting backups in a single vault"],"answer":2,"explain":"<strong>Ensuring a downloaded confidential report cannot be forwarded or printed by recipients</strong> — controlling actions like forwarding and printing after download requires IRM's persistent usage rights, which storage encryption alone cannot enforce.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Protecting data only while it sits in one encrypted bucket</b>: at-rest encryption in one store is exactly what storage-level encryption already covers.</span><span class='qd'><b>Encrypting a database's underlying volumes</b>: volume encryption is a storage control, not per-object usage rights.</span><span class='qd'><b>Encrypting backups in a single vault</b>: backup encryption protects the vault contents but does not govern recipient actions on distributed files.</span>"},{"id":"D2-100","domain":2,"obj":"2.8","diff":"hard","q":"During a forensic review, the team must show that cloud audit logs were not altered between collection and analysis. Which technique provides the strongest assurance?","options":["Storing a copy in a second folder","Renaming the files with the date","Compressing the logs into an archive","Generating cryptographic hashes at collection and verifying them at each handling step, with write-once storage"],"answer":3,"explain":"<strong>Generating cryptographic hashes at collection and verifying them at each handling step, with write-once storage</strong> — hashing at collection plus verification at every step and immutable storage cryptographically proves the logs were not altered.<br><span class='qwhy'>Why the other options are wrong:</span><span class='qd'><b>Storing a copy in a second folder</b>: a second mutable copy provides no proof against alteration.</span><span class='qd'><b>Renaming the files with the date</b>: filenames carry no integrity guarantee and are trivially changed.</span><span class='qd'><b>Compressing the logs into an archive</b>: compression changes the container but does not detect or prevent tampering with contents.</span>"}]);
